Wow! Lotta stuff to respond to.<br>
Edward, as to my pissing you off because I make you<br>
agree with me, you do well fighting fire with fire. I <br>
wake up at night thinking about things that all of us<br>
have posted and wondering again, if what I believed<br>
for years is actually true. Thank you all for ruining<br>
my sleep and opening my mind.<br><br>
N.A.C.<br>
Thanks for coming back with your best stuff. I like<br>
this.<br><br>
Cook, It pained me graeatly when I learned that the<br>
Vietnamese government reated re-education camps and<br>
did many of the opressive actions. <br><br>
Ho Chi Min was a Vietnamese Nationalist. His ties to<br>
Russia were because he needed support from outside major<br>
powers, and he was denied that support by the US. He<br>
came to us first.<br><br>
As for your response to the &quot;Cheap labor&quot; statment and<br>
don't we all shop for a bargain. The difference is that<br>
we useds the CIA to destabilize governments, and we<br>
placed dictators inpower in other countries or supported<br>
those in power purely for economic gain. We supported<br>
dictators, tyrants etc. whose economic policies, and<br>
political policies were/are in direct contrast to what <br>
we believe. We did this for economic gain. Cheap bargains<br>
are good, but controlling the market through force is <br>
not how the game should be played.<br><br>
Tom, WOW. A very powerful post, thank you.I think one of the <br>
things I regret most in all the actions of the anti-war<br>
movement was the lack of respect and dignity afforded<br>
the Vets by the anti-war protesters. <br><br>
I remember in 1968, on 42nd st and 8th Ave in N.Y.C.<br>
talking to someone I had never met before on a street <br>
corner trying to convince them that the war was wrong.<br>
I told that person, he was about 18 years old, that<br>
soldiers were killing innocent women and children and<br>
that like murder. He started crying and screaming at<br>
me. He told me that his brother was killed in Vietnam,<br>
and I could not call him a murderer and that I was an<br>
ass for equating the the work of the soldiers and murder.<br>
I realized at that point, that we were talking about human<br>
beings doing the best they could, doing what they thought <br>
was right and that I was an ass for saying what I had<br>
said. Seeing the war through his eyes for that moment<br>
was one of the most memorable things for me about my<br>
anti-war work. I never said (or believed) that assinine<br>
statement again. Apologies to this man, wherever he may be.<br>
PS. Several people were there, it got loud and then some,<br>
I barely escaped without having myself and my car destroyed.<br>
Served me right! <br><br>
eh,,Cook that might have been one riot you<br>
were slow to break up (laugh).<br><br>
After that experience I spent some time visiting with<br>
soldiers at a Coffee House outside of Ft. Dix, NJ to<br>
get a better sense of what the war ment to soldiers. I<br>
still felt that the war was wrong, but I got a much better<br>
understanding of why people were going and the delemna<br>
many people were facing.<br><br>
Both Communism and Capitalism sound can sound like a<br>
good philosophy. <br><br>
Each according to their ability, each according to their<br>
need. That is a philosophy that sounds good and caring. That<br>
a good strong society can be built on.<br><br>
Let each do what they can, the market forces will keep<br>
the prices in line, things will get produced that are<br>
needed because that is what people will buy. Let un-<br>
fettered capitalism lead to new products and new inventions<br>
raising the standard of living for all who live under<br>
this system.<br><br>
Both sound good, but that is not the problem. The problem is<br>
lust for power, the untamed desire to control and dominate.<br>
We see it with both systems, where Stalan, and his ilk<br>
have used a 'good' system to opress millions. We have<br>
seen it with the Bosnian debacle. They were in-check<br>
until the fall of Communism and then... Lesser examples<br>
of Nixonian democracy. His example was not one of<br>
democracy in action. Geo. Washington and his friends<br>
were slave owners. Doesn't sound too democratic to me.<br><br>
I often lean towards a decentralized model of government,<br>
as one that I think has promise, but I see many flaws with that<br>
as well. <br><br>
I don't know what the answer is, but I see<br>
the problem and fight like hell to make it better in <br>
any way I can. I think that that is something in common<br>
that those who faught for the war and thoses who faught<br>
against it have in common. That is the point that allows<br>
me to respect those who did differently than I did. It is<br>
clear to me that in 1998 no one has figured out the answer.<br><br>
I think that many people called themselves Communist because<br>
they believed in a society that was not based on a dod -<br>
eat-dog market philosophy, where people got what they<br>
needed and contributed what they could. For Many of us,<br>
that felt real different than what we were doing in <br>
Vietnam, and at home during the 60's. I don't thnk that<br>
I know that it did not mean that they were affiliated with<br>
a Communist party or were taking orders from the Kremlin.<br><br>

